{{for|the political march|Ram Rath Yatra}} {{EngvarB|date=September 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Ratha Yatra <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. --> |type = Hindu |longtype = Religious |image = Rath Yatra Puri 07-11027.jpg |caption = Three chariots of the deities with the Temple in the background, Puri |observedby = [[Hindu]]s |begins = [[Ashadha]] Shukla [[Dwitiya]] |ends = Ashadha Shukla [[Dashami]] |date2018 = 14 July |date2039 = |observances = |relatedto = }}
'''Ratha Yatra''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|r|ʌ|θ|ə|_|ˈ|j|ɑː|t|r|ə}}), also referred to as '''Rathayatra''', '''Rathajatra''' or '''Chariot festival''' is any public procession in a chariot.<ref name="vemsani135"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Christophe Jaffrelot|title=The Hindu Nationalist Movement and Indian Politics: 1925 to the 1990s|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=iVsfVOTUnYEC |year= 1999|publisher= Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-024602-5|pages=416–421}}</ref> The term particularly refers to the annual Rathayatra in [[Odisha]], [[Jharkhand]], West Bengal and other [[East India]]n states, particularly the [[Odia culture|Odia festival]] <ref name="ClausDiamond2003">{{cite book|author1=Peter J. Claus|author2=Sarah Diamond|author3=Margaret Ann Mills|title=South Asian Folklore: An Encyclopedia : Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ienxrTPHzzwC&pg=PA515|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-93919-5|pages=515–}}</ref> that involve a public procession with a chariot with deities [[Jagannath]] ([[Vishnu]] avatar), [[Balabhadra]] (his brother), [[Subhadra]] (his sister) and [[Sudarshana Chakra]] (his weapon) on a [[ratha]], a wooden [[deula]]-shaped chariot. It attracts over a million Hindu pilgrims who join the procession each year.<ref name="vemsani135">{{cite book|author=Lavanya Vemsani |title=Krishna in History, Thought, and Culture: An Encyclopedia of the Hindu Lord of Many Names|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4fw2DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA135|year=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-211-3|page=135}}</ref><ref name=Banglapedia>{{cite book |last=Mandai |first=Paresh Chandra |year=2012 |chapter=Rathayatra |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Rathayatra |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>
''Rathayatra'' processions have been historically common in Vishnu-related (Jagannath, Rama, Krishna) traditions in [[Hinduism]] across India,<ref>{{cite book|author=Bruce M. Sullivan|title=The A to Z of Hinduism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xU4ZdatgRysC |year=2001|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8108-4070-6|pages=100, 166, 209}}</ref> in Shiva-related traditions,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pratapaditya Pal|author2=Stephen P. Huyler|author3=John E. Cort et al.|title=Puja and Piety: Hindu, Jain, and Buddhist Art from the Indian Subcontinent|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NXolDQAAQBAJ |year =2016|publisher=University of California Press|isbn= 978-0-520-28847-8|pages=72–74 with Figures 23–25}}</ref> saints and goddesses in Nepal,<ref>{{cite book|author=J.P. Losty|editor= David M. Waterhouse|title=The Origins of Himalayan Studies: Brian Houghton Hodgson in Nepal and Darjeeling, 1820-1858|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=_rhgqGA2nKoC&pg=PA94 |year=2004|publisher= Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-31215-8|pages=93–94 with Figure 5.11}}</ref> with [[Tirthankaras]] in [[Jainism]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Virendra Kumar Sharma|title=History of Jainism: With Special Reference to Mathurā|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M3vXAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=DK|isbn=978-81-246-0195-2|page=162}}</ref> as well as tribal folk religions found in the eastern states of India.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ajit K. Singh|title=Tribal Festivals of Bihar: A Functional Analysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gvLiAsmvx6IC |year= 1982|publisher= Concept| pages= 30–33}}</ref> Notable ratha yatras in India include the [[Ratha Yatra (Puri)|Ratha yatra of Puri]], the [[Dhamrai Rathayatra|Dhamrai Ratha Yatra]] and the [[Rathayatra of Mahesh|Ratha Yatra of Mahesh]]. Hindu communities outside India, such as in Singapore, celebrate Rathayatra such as those associated with [[Jagannath]], [[Krishna]], [[Shiva]] and [[Mariamman]].<ref name="Jacobsen2008p159">{{cite book|author=Vineeta Sinha|editor=Knut A. Jacobsen|title=South Asian Religions on Display: Religious Processions in South Asia and in the Diaspora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WT2odZ7_d7MC&pg=PA163|year=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-07459-4|pages=159–174}}</ref> According to Knut Jacobsen, a ''Rathayatra'' has religious origins and meaning, but the events have a major community heritage, social sharing and cultural significance to the organizers and participants.<ref>{{cite book|author=Knut A. Jacobsen|editor=Knut A. Jacobsen|title=South Asian Religions on Display: Religious Processions in South Asia and in the Diaspora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WT2odZ7_d7MC |year=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-07459-4|pages=8–11, 200–201}}</ref>
{{Infobox | title = ''Ratha yatra'' in Hinduism | image = {{image array|perrow=2|width=150|height=120 | image1 = Kalpathy Chariot festival last day.jpg| caption1 = Viswanatha ([[Shiva]]) and Visalakshi ([[Parvati]]) ''rathayatra'' in Kerala | image2 = India - Kanchipuram - 022 - chariot unveiled for upcoming festival (2508349542).jpg| caption2 = Ratha in Tamil Nadu | image3 = FeteVarkala.jpg| caption3 = Krishna and Arjuna at a ''ratha'' festival | image4 = Living Goddess Kumari in Chariot during Indrajatra festival in Kathmandu.JPG| caption4 = A girl as goddess in a Nepalese ''ratha'' | image5 = A Krishna Radha couple at the Festival Of Chariots 2010.jpg| caption5 = [[Krishna]] and [[Radha]], London chariot festival | image6 = Srinivasa Perumal roof.jpg| caption6 = Thiruvizha festival }} |caption = Rathayatra are festival processions, occasions for religious, social and cultural celebrations. }}
== Etymology == Ratha-yatra is derived two Sanskrit words, ''Ratha'' ([http://dsalsrv02.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/macdonell_query.py?qs=%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%A5&searchhws=yes रथ]) which means chariot or carriage, and ''yātrā'' ([http://dsalsrv02.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/macdonell_query.py?qs=%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BE&searchhws=yes यात्रा]) which means journey or pilgrimage.<ref>{{cite book|author=Nori J. Muster|title=Betrayal of the Spirit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z3uoAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA38|year=2013|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-09499-6|page=38}}</ref> In other Indian languages such as Odia, the phonetic equivalents are used, such as ''ratha'' and ''jatra''. Other names for the festival are ''ratha jatra'' or ''chariot festival''.
==Description== {{expand section|date=June 2017}} Rathayatra'' is a journey in a chariot accompanied by the public. It typically refers to a procession (journey) of deities, people dressed like deities, or simply religious saints and political leaders.<ref name="Michaels1996p270">{{cite book|author1=Michaels|author2=Cornelia Vogelsanger|author3=Annette Wilke|title=Wild Goddesses in India and Nepal: Proceedings of an International Symposium, Berne and Zurich, November 1994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1wbXAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=P. Lang|isbn=978-3-906756-04-2|pages=270–285}}</ref> The term appears in medieval texts of India such as the [[Puranas]], which mention the Rathayatra of [[Surya]] (Sun god), of [[Devi]] (Mother goddess), and of [[Vishnu]]. These chariot journeys have elaborate celebrations where the individuals or the deities come out of a temple accompanied by the public journeying with them through the ''Ksetra'' (region, streets) to another temple or to the river or the sea. Sometimes the festivities include returning back to the sacrosanctum of the temple.<ref name="Michaels1996p270"/><ref name=Banglapedia/>
==Places== {{Hinduism small}} {{Refimprove section|date=February 2017}}
===Jagannath Rath Yatra at Puri (Odisha)=== {{Main|Ratha-Yatra (Puri)}} [[File:Bahuda Jatra, Nabakalebara 2015.jpg|thumb|Rathayatra in Odisha]] Triads are usually worshiped in the sanctum of the [[Jagannath Temple, Puri|temple]] at [[Puri]], but once during the month of [[Asadha]] (Rainy Season of [[Odisha]], usually falling in month of June or July), they are brought out onto the Bada Danda (main street of Puri) and travel (3&nbsp;km) to the Shri [[Gundicha Temple]], in huge chariots ([[ratha]]), allowing the public to have [[darśana]] (Holy view). This festival is known as Rath Yatra, meaning the journey ([[yatra]]) of the chariots (ratha). The Rathas are huge wheeled wooden structures, which are built anew every year and are pulled by the devotees. The chariot for Jagannath is approximately 45 feet high and 35 feet square and takes about 2 months to construct.{{Sfn|Starza|1993|p=16}} The artists and painters of Puri decorate the cars and paint flower petals and other designs on the wheels, the wood-carved charioteer and horses, and the inverted lotuses on the wall behind the throne.{{Sfn|Das|1982|p=40}} The huge chariots of Jagannath pulled during Rath Yatra is the etymological origin of the English word [[Juggernaut]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Juggernaut-Definition and Meaning|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/juggernaut|publisher=Merriam Webster Dictionary|accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref> The Ratha-Yatra is also termed as the Shri Gundicha yatra.
The most significant ritual associated with the Ratha-Yatra is the ''chhera pahara.'' During the festival, the [[Gajapati Kingdom|Gajapati King]] wears the outfit of a sweeper and sweeps all around the deities and chariots in the ''Chera Pahara'' (sweeping with water) ritual. The Gajapati King cleanses the road before the chariots with a gold-handled broom and sprinkles sandalwood water and powder with utmost devotion. As per the custom, although the Gajapati King has been considered the most exalted person in the [[Kalinga (historical kingdom)|Kalinga]]n kingdom, he still renders the menial service to Jagannath. This ritual signified that under the lordship of Jagannath, there is no distinction between the powerful sovereign Gajapati King and the most humble devotee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Karan|first=Jajati|title=Lord Jagannath yatra to begin soon|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/lord-jagannath-yatra-to-begin-soon/68263-3-2.html|accessdate=28 November 2012|newspaper=IBN Live|date=4 July 2008}}</ref>
''Chera pahara'' is held on two days, on the first day of the Ratha Yatra, when the deities are taken to garden house at [[Mausi Maa Temple]] and again on the last day of the festival, when the deities are ceremoniously brought back to the Shri Mandir.
As per another ritual, when the deities are taken out from the Shri Mandir to the Chariots in ''Pahandi vijay''.
In the Ratha Yatra, the three deities are taken from the Jagannath Temple in the chariots to the [[Gundicha Temple]], where they stay for nine days. Thereafter, the deities again ride the chariots back to Shri Mandir in ''bahuda yatra''. On the way back, the three chariots halt at the Mausi Maa Temple and the deities are offered ''Poda Pitha,'' a kind of baked cake which are generally consumed by the people of Odisha.
[[File:Kolkata rath yatra.jpg|thumb|258x258px|Rath Yatra Festival in [[Kolkata]]]] The observance of the Rath Yatra of Jagannath dates back to the period of the Puranas. Vivid descriptions of this festival are found in [[Brahma Purana]], [[Padma Purana]], and [[Skanda Purana]]. Kapila Samhita also refers to Rath Yatra. In [[Moghul]] period also, King Ramsingh of [[Jaipur]], [[Rajasthan]] has been described as organizing the Rath Yatra in the 18th Century. In [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], Kings of [[Mayurbhanj District|Mayurbhanj]] and [[Parlakhemundi]] were organizing the Rath Yatra, though the most grand festival in terms of scale and popularity takes place at Puri.
Moreover, Starza{{Sfn|Starza|1993|p=133}} notes that the ruling [[Eastern Ganga Dynasty|Ganga dynasty]] instituted the Rath Yatra at the completion of the great temple around 1150 AD. This festival was one of those Hindu festivals that was reported to the Western world very early. [[Friar Odoric]] of Pordenone visited India in 1316-1318, some 20 years after [[Marco Polo]] had dictated the account of his travels while in a [[Genoa|Genoese]] prison.{{Sfn|Mitter|1977|p=10}} In his own account of 1321, Odoric reported how the people put the "idols" on chariots, and the King and Queen and all the people drew them from the "church" with song and music.{{Sfn|Starza|1993|p=129}} {{Sfn|Das|1982|p=48}}
===International Jagannath Ratha Yatra=== [[Image:Rath Yatra.jpg|thumb|Rath Yatra Festival in [[New York City|New York]]]] The Ratha Yatra festival has become a common sight in most major cities of the world since 1968 through the [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|Hare Krishna]] movement. Local chapters put on the festival annually in over a hundred cities worldwide.<ref>[http://www.festivalofindia.org/ Festival of India]</ref>
===Dhamrai Jagannath Roth festival=== {{main|Dhamrai Jagannath Roth}} '''Dhamrai Jagannath Rath''' is a chariot temple, a [[Ratha|Roth]], dedicated to the [[Hindu]] God [[Jagannath]] located in [[Dhamrai]], [[Bangladesh]]. The annual Jagannath Roth Jatra is a famous Hindu festival attracting thousands of people. The Roth Jatra in Dhamrai is one of the most important events for the Hindu community of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rathajatra festival today|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1758735781.html|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The New Nation, Dhaka{{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|date=24 June 2009}}</ref> The original historical Roth was burnt down by the Pakistan Army in 1971<ref name="Banglapedia"/> The Roth has since been rebuilt with Indian assistance.
=== Ratha Yatra of Mahesh=== {{main|Rathayatra of Mahesh}} '''The Ratha Yatra of Mahesh''' is the Second oldest [[Temple car|chariot]] festival in [[India]] (after [[Rath Yatra]] at [[Puri]]) and oldest in [[Bengal]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Rathayatra celebrated in West Bengal |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/004200807041757.htm |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=4 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-10-18 }}</ref> having been celebrated since 1396 A.D.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bengal celebrates Rathayatra festival |url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/india/news/article_1330596.php/Bengal_celebrates_Rathayatra_festival |work=Monsters and Critics |date=16 July 2007 |accessdate=2008-10-18 }}</ref> It is a month-long festival held at Mahesh in [[Serampore]] of [[West Bengal]] and a grand fair is held at that time. People throng to have a share in pulling the long ropes (Roshi) attached to the chariots of Lord [[Jagannath]], [[Balarama]] and [[Subhadra]] on the journey from the temple to Gundicha Bari (Masir bari) and back.
==Examples== {{double image|right|Carfestival.jpg|220|Rato Machhidranath.jpg|100|Left: A 1914 painting of Rathayatra in Chennai; Right: A [[Matsyendranath]] Rathayatra in Nepal}} * [[Ratha-Yatra (Puri)]], at Puri in the state of Odisha, is the largest and most visited Rath Yatra in the world attracting a large crowd every year. * [[Rathayatra of Mahesh|Rathayatra of Mahesh in]] [[Serampore]], [[West Bengal]] Ratha Yatra is the second oldest in the world. * Rath Yatra of [[Kolkata]] is the second largest Rath Yatra in the world. * Rath Yatra also takes place in [[Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat|Gujarat State]], which is known to be the third largest in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rathyatralive.com/ahmedabad-rath-yatra-jamalpur-jagannath-temple/48/ |title=About Ahmedabad Rath Yatra : Jamalpur Jagannath Temple}}</ref> * Sukinda Ratha Yatra in Odisha is also known to attract a large number of devotees. * [[Dhamrai Jagannath Roth]], at Dhamrai in Bangladesh, is the most famous Rath Yatra in Bangladesh. * [[ISKCON]] [[Dhaka]] Ratha Yatra is the second famous Rath Yatra in Bangladesh. * [[Rajbalhat]] Ratha Yatra, West Bengal, India. [[File:Nabadwip somaj bari nrisingha mandir bigroho.jpg|thumb|left|The Ratha-Yatra of Jagannath In Nabadwip features unusual images with hands.<ref>[http://www.anandabazar.com/district/nodia-murshidabbad/worship-of-lord-jagannath-followed-by-a-different-style-in-nabadwip-1.636993?ref=nodia-murshidabbad-new-stry Nabadwip Jagannath]</ref>]] * People of [[Bastar district|Bastar region]] observe Ratha yatra during [[Dussehara]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2003-09-25/news/27514315_1_bastar-colours-temple |title=Dussehra in Bastar -- a riot of colours - Economic Times |first=Partha |last=S Banerjee|work=indiatimes.com |year=2008|quote=The Bastar royal family figures prominently in the script and the props include a huge chariot that is first built, then ritually 'stolen', and then again recovered and pulled ceremonially through the streets of Jagdalpur |accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.oneindia.in/2008/10/09/tribals-celebrate-unique-dussehra-in-bastar-1223542981.html |title=Tribals celebrate unique Dussehra in Bastar - Oneindia News |first= |last= |work=news.oneindia.in |year=2008 |quote=The another attraction of this 'tribal Dusshra', is a double- decked Rath (Chariot) with eight wheels and weighing about 30 tonnes. |accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref> * Radha Rani Rath Yatra, held at the [[Radha Madhav Dham#Festivals|Radha Madhav Dham]] temple near Austin, Texas, U.S.A. * Rath yatra in [[Silicon Valley]] is organized at [[Golden Gate Park]], [[San Francisco]], California, USA * Ratha Yatra is celebrated in more than 108 cities around the world.
